<HEADLINE>
CAKES, DINNERS MOST POPULAR MOTHER'S DAY GIFTS: SURVEY
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  May 12 (CNA) 05/12/07  19:52:18 (By Y.F. Low)
</P>
<P>
Most Internet users in Taiwan spend no more than NT$6,000 on
Mother Day's gifts, with cakes and dinners being the most popular
gift choices, according to the results of a recent survey
released by a market research company.
</P>
<P>
The survey conducted by InsightXplorer shows that cakes and
feasts are each favored by 28.1 percent of the respondents.
</P>
<P>
Other common Mother's Day gifts include cash or gift vouchers
(18.9 percent) , skin care products (10.5 percent) , jewelry (7.2
percent), clothing (5.1 percent), health food (4.5 percent) ,
tour packages (3.8 percent) , shoes (3.7 percent) and mobile
phones (3.2 percent).
</P>
<P>
The survey found that 33.2 percent of respondents said they plan
to spend NT$1,001 to NT$3,000 on Mother's Day gifts, 25.1 percent
plan to spend no more than NT$1,000, and 22.9 percent plan to
spend NT$3,001 to NT$6,000.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 12 percent of respondents plan to spend more than
NT$9,000 on the gifts.
</P>
<P>
On the places to shop for Mother's Day gifts, 41.9 percent of the
respondents will go to department stores or shopping malls, 26.7
percent will go to hypermarkets.
</P>
<P>
Online shopping and online auctions are favored by 15.9 percent
and 10 percent of the respondents, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows that Internet users under 19 years old prefer to
shop for the gifts at household product stores, such as Poya
Living Mart, and health and personal care stores such as Cosmed
and Watsons, while those over 40 years old prefer hypermarkets.
</P>
<P>
Among respondents planning to give skin care products for
Mother's Day, 64.2 percent will visit department stores or
shopping malls, 29.7 percent will go to health and personal care
stores, 29.5 percent will visit online shopping sites.
</P>
<P>
Among respondents planning to buy jewelry, 65.4 percent will go
to department stores or shopping malls, 36.2 percent will visit
online shopping sites.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted from April 27-28 on 5,086 Internet users
in Taiwan.
</P>
